{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_junco_ver01/data/sn83045499/00393342158/1945092201/0550.xml":{"full_text":"Daily Alaska Empire\nPublished every evening except Sunday by the\nIMPIHr PRINTING rOMTANT\nerror.! and Main Streets, Juneau, Alaska.\nUN troy MONriBN President\nDOROTHY TROY 1.7NGO Vice-President\nWI1.1.IAM R CARTER Editor and Manager\nELMER A FRIEND Managing Editor\nALTRED 7.ENUER Business Manager\nfiltered In the Post orflce In Juneau ns Second Class Matter.\nSUBSCRIPTION BATES:\nDelivered by carrier in Juneau and Douglas for SI.Ml per month;\nmonth*. SH.OU: one >rar. >15.00\nBy mall, postage paid, at the followlnn rates:\nOne yrfti. In advance. 115.00; six months, In advance, 17 50:\n\u00a9ne month. In advance i-1 50\nSubscribers will confer a favor If they will promptly notiry\nthe Business Of lice of uny failure or Irrenularlty In the de\nlivery of their papers.\nTelephone News Office. G02: Business Office. 374.\nMEMBER OF AHWOCIATFD PRESS\nThe Associated Pr< s Is exclusively entitled to the use for\nrepubltcatton cl all news dispatches credited to It or not other\nwise credited In this paper and also the local news published\nherein.\nNATIONAL REPRESENTATIVES Alaska Newspapers. 1411\nFourth Avenue Blcit Seattle, Wash.\nKlllLDINU OUTLOOK\nWartime controls over private construction will\nsoon be removed and the way cleared tor a revival\not building activity capable of providing a tremendously\nimportant source of demand for men and materials\nduring the transition period. President Truman\nstated in his address to Congress, \"The largest single\nopportunity for the rapid postwar expansion of\nprivate investment and employment lies in the field\nof housing, both urban and rural.\" Consequently, the\nmore quickly the hoped-for building revival gets under\nway, the greater will be the assistance rendered by the\nindustry in sustaining business and providing jobs\nduring the most critical stages of reconversion. For\nthat reason every effort should be made to overcome\nobstacles which prevent blueprint plans from being\ntransformed into real structures.\nOn the optimistic side the construction industry\nis confronted by a tremendous pentup demand for\nprivate residences, stores, and public buildings of all\nsorts. Normally annual construction outlays, public\nand private, are estimated at more than 10 per cent\nof national income. In view of the immense backlog\nof unsatisfied demands, coupled witli the great increase\n'.hat has occurred in national income during the war\nyears, official estimates of 15 billion dollars to be\n^pent on building by 1950 seems not unreasonable.\nSuch a scale of buiding would provide direct employ\nment for about three million people, it is estimated,\nnot to mention a large and varied volume of indirect\nemployment. However, 1950 seems a long way off to\nthose who are struggling with the immediately pressing\nproblems of reconversion unemployment. It is im\nportant, therefore, to try to hasten the date when\nbuilding activity will attain its postwar peak in order\nthat the construction industry may make the maximum\ncontribution of which it is capable to postwar revival.\nDifferences of opinion exist as to the possibility\nof the industry\u2019s staging a speedy comeback in force.\nAnd there is also a disposition in some quarters to\nstress obstacles to revival of residential building\nactivity for selfish reasons. For example, a survey\nconducted by the Wall Street Journal in various large\ncities throughout the country among real estate deal\ners creates the impression that the day when new\nhomes can be benight is a long way off. Naturally\nsuch opinions have to be taken with many grains of\nsalt, since real estate dealers with old houses on their\nhands can hardly be expected to spoil their market\nby heralding the advent of the new houses soon to\ncome. Then, too, there is a disposition to delay ex\necuting new building plan in the hope that later on\nconstruction costs may decline. The answer to those\nfavoring a waiting polity i that the sooner we accept\n11he fact that postwar construction costs are going to\nbe well above prewar levels and get along with plan\nning, the greater the insurance against a postwar\ndepression that would destroy hopes of a major revival\nI of private construction activity.\nCurrent shortages ol lumber and other construc\ntion materials, as well as reported serious shortages\nI of skilled construction labor, art undoubtedly factors\nto be reckoned with. But they are only temporary\ni obstacles to revival that can be surmounted provided\ni the resolution to overcome them exists. Already it is\nJ being said that lumber, one of the chief bottlenecks\nI to speedy resumption of private residential building,\nwill soon be available in sufficient quantity to permit\nthe industry to get off to a good start within a few\nmonths. Shortages of skilled building trades work\ners, especially in those communities that have suf\nfered seriously in the past from the high-handed de\nmands of unions primarily interested in monopolizing\njobs for their members, present a more difficult\nproblem. Provided the unions can be induced to\nacquiesce in plans for utilizing unskilled labor under\nexpert direction, we have no doubt that the building\nlabor supply will equal the demand and may even\nexceed it in the next few years. Indeed, it appears\nthat one of the most formidable hindrances to a\nrapidly expanding volume of private construction in\nthe coming months is a generally pessimistic attitude\nof mind. Such pessimism tends to paralyze initiative\nin overcoming otherwise removable obstacles in the\nway of a major expansion of the construction industry.\nThe Washington\nMerry Go Round\n(Continued from Page One)\nbattles with the White House.\nThe Republicans were told, for\ninstance, that they will not get a\nchance to vote on abolishing the\ndraft because the Democratic lead\nership will keep the issue from a\nvote until the pressure gets\nheavier. Then at the right psycho\nlogical moment, it was predicted,\nthe White House will abolish the\ndraft by executive order, thereby\nhogging the credit.\nOtherwse, there was little done\nin the caucus. It was supposed to\nwork up a legislative program, but\nlittle of constructive nature was\nsaid. Brassy-lunged John Tuber of\nAuburn. N. Y\u201e ranking Republican\non the House Appropriations Com\nmittee, made his usual speech call\ning for economy in government.\nAs usual, he was seconded by\nHarold Knutson of Manhattan\nBeach, Minn., ranking Republican\non the Ways and Means Committee.\nOnly once did the Republicans\nhear anything which made them\nwince a bit. This came from Pro\ngressive Charley La Follette of\nEvansville, Ind\u201e who spoke on the\npending legislation to create a Fair\nEmployment Practices Committee.\nBecause it was apparent that the\nRepublicans are not bestirring\nthemselves to put through this\nlegislation, La Follette reminded\nthem that their 1944 platform defi\nnitely calls for support for FEPC.\nLa Follette scolded them lor failing\nto push their own program, and\ncriticized, without naming any\nnames, a number of fellow Con\ngressmen who last year told cam\npaign audiences that Governor\nDewey was advocating progressive\nmeasures merely as a means of\ngetting votes.\n\"It's about tme we stopped cru\ncifying our own candidates,\" said\nIndiana's La Follette. \"If we are\nto be honest about this whole\nthing, why don't we select as our\ncandidate someone in Congress\nwhose vote has never deviated\nfrom the Republican policy? Let's\nput up such a man and let him run\nwith this simple platform: 'I stand\non the record of the Republican\nParty in Congress\u2019.\"\nMost of his colleagues either did\nnot catch or did not like this\nsarcasm.\nQUIZZING GERMAN Oi l 1< l.ltS\nOne of file smartest operators\nattached to the U. S. Strategic\nBombing Survey, v.hich studied\nbomb damage in Germany, was\nSgt. Paul Baran former Harvard\ninstructor, and a refugee from\nHitler, Baran, who has the map of\nPalestine written all over his face,\nwas given the job of interviewing\none of the great leaders ol the\nGet man Army Col. Gen. Fran/\nHaider.\nUp until Himmler eased him out\nin 194\"!, Haider ran the German\nArmy. However, he was forced to\nsit before Sgt. Baran lor two long\nhours and answer rapid-fire ques\ntions. After the interview, Col\nGen. Haider, with considerable re\nspect in his voice, said:\n\"May I ask my interviewer a\nquestion?\u201d\n\"Is all American Intelligence on\na level with this interrogation?\"\nBaran replied that he thought it\nwas.\n\"Then I would like to say, sir,\u201d\nreplied Hitler's former Chief of\nStaff, \u201cthat your knowledge of\nGerman's strategic plans is greater\nthan the Fuehrer's.\u201d\n\nNAZI FACTORIES UNDAMAGED\nA significant backstage argu\nment is now taking place regarding\nthe results of the U. S. Strategic\nbombing Survey in Europe.\nConclusive, though still unoffi\ncial results of this survey, show\nthat bombing of German war\nplants was not as effective as the\nair forces claimed. On the other\nhand, the bombing of German rail\nroads and transportaton centers\nwas extremely effective. This had\nmore to do than almost anything\nelse with disrupting the German\nArmy. Supplies and troops could\nnot move with U, S. fliers con\nstantly strafing and blasting them.\nMany German factories, however,\nwere too deeply buried in the\nground or different parts too\nwidely separated to suffer much\ndamage. The famous Schweinfurt\nball-bearing plant, for instance, was\nnot put out of commission, de\nspite of the fact that t!0 U. S.\nbombers and 600 American airmen\nwere lost over it in one raid.\nGen. \"Hap\" Arnold, Chief of the\nAir Forces, went to great lengths\nafter the first Schweinfurt raid to\nshow that this heavy loss was com\npensated for by damage to vital\nball-bearing production. However,\nsurveys of the factory showed that\nthis was not the case.\nSome people inside the War De\npartment, therefore, are not too\nhappy about proposed publication\nof the lull survey. Others, how\never, are for full and complete\npublicity.\nOne man who did an A-l job\nwith tile Strategic Bombing Survey\nwas Henry C. Alexander, vice\npresident of the J. P. Morgan\nbanking house. Alexander rolled\nup his sleeves, bucked red tape,\nand strangely enough cooperated\n100 per cent with New Deal offi\ncials in Europe. In fact he proved\nsuch a refreshing influence that\nsteps may be taken to bring him\nto Washington in an important\ngovernment position.\nWhile officials admit that some\nbusiness executives attached to the\nbombing survey took advantage of\ntheir position to carry home photos\nof new German patents and inven\ntions, nevertheless they say the\nsurvey gathered some extremely\nimportant records and ferreted out\ncertain Nazi leaders.\nFor instance, Nazi civilian pro\nduction chief Seebauer was picked\nup by survey officials near Salz\nburg right under the nose of the\nAmerican Army. He was working\nin a hotel where American officers\nCrossword Puzzle\nACROSS\n1. Part of a play\n4. Containers\n9. Strike gently\n12. And not\n13. Over\n14. Cereal\n15. Before\n1C. Orchid meal\n17. Early English\nmoney'\n18. Squanders\n20. Rat-catchin*\nanimal\nAttempted\nFish eggs\nPunctuation\nmark\n27. Buntinglike\nfabric\n31. The herb dill\n32. Tell thought\nlessly\n33. Incline the\nhead\n22.\n24.\n34.\n35.\n38.\n39.\n41.\n42.\n44.\n46.\n47.\n48.\n50.\n63.\n66.\n57.\n59.\nCO.\n61.\n62.\nChinese\nmeasure\nChairman of\nthe House\nCompass point\nShip\u2019s record\nTardy\nUnclose\nEnliven\nLevel tracts\nalong a river\nNegative\nMore sensitive\nPut into action\nUpright parts\nof stairs\nProfound\nreverence\nOrgans of scent\nPinch\nRange of\nknowledge\nEskimo canoe\nHigh pointed\nhill\n63. Unit of work\n64. Repairs\n65. Pigpen\nDOWN\n1. Afresh\n2. Mexican Indian\n3. Viaduct\n4. Protein of milk\n5. Humble\n6. Sun\n7. Always\n8. Apart\n9. Body-builcttng;\nnutrient\n10. Northern point\nof the Isle\nof Man\nIt. Pull apart\n19. Jogs\n21. Male cat\n23. Makes public\n20. Kind ui lily\n26. Vegetable\n28. Accept\n29. Nine-part\ncomposition\n30. Blissful region*\n32. Defeat\n36. Precious metal\n37. Paris in a play\n40. Chinese herb\n43. Forebears\n43. Witticism\n46. Gambols\n49. Mountain\nnymph\n50. Cook with dry\nheat\n51. Pitcher\n52. City in New\nYork state\n51 Tumult\n58. iniquity\nHAPPY BIRTHDAY\nSeptember 22, 194!)\n\nThomas A. Morgan\nAlberta Carlson\nMrs. C. F. McNutt\nFrank Maver\nMrs. Louise Heisel\nMargaret Femmer\nT. J. Selby\ni Lorraine Carlson\nMrs. Charles Fox\nDorothy Thibodeau\nDonald Hayes\nj\nSeptember 23, 1945\n\nH E. Simmons\ni Margaret Woodford\nGary Alan Strand\nMary Pinkley\nCarl Danielson\nAndrea Fleek\n9 Oroville Porter\nMrs. J. C. Spicket\n9 Estyr Jackson\n9 Anko Dapcevich\n9 Art Carlson\ni HOROSCOPE\nj \u201cThe stars incline\nbut do not compel\u201d\nSUNDAY, SEPTEMBER 23\nBenefic aspects dominate today\ni but Saturn is in threatening mien.\nMuch uplift of spirit because of\nI good news is presaged.\nHeart And Home\nPoise and confidence should be\nprevalent under this sway which\nbrings clear vision regarding future\nfamily plans. Women are under\nfavorable planetary influences that\npromise much joy.\nBusiness Affairs\nYoung financial leaders will\nemerge this autumn and will bring\nto the business world broad views\nand trained minds. Capitalists who\nlealize that broad-gauge coopera\n1 lion with labor is necessary will\nI prosper.\nNational Issues\nAmerican ideas concerning rec\nreation and amusement must be\nI radically changed, it is forecast, if\nthe nation is to reach its best de\nvelopment. Ai my records prove how\nmuch is lacking in our physical\n'attainments and now is the time\nfor general correction.\nInternational Affairs\nAlthough the stars indicate pro\ncrastination, the United States is\nto frame a foreign policy that will\nadd much to the strength of the\ngovernment. Our national kindliness\nmust have a strong mixture of\ni force in dealing with other na\ntions.\nI Persons whose birthdate it is\ni have the augury of a year of re\nadjustments that will be profitable.\nJ Love affairs may be too diverting\nj for best success in money matters.\nChildren born on this day prob\ni ably will be artistic and intelligent.\nI They should be carefully trained\nI in practical tasks.\ni MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 24\nBenefic aspects rule today which\nshould bring much cause for re\njoicing and happy planning. Good\nI for initiative.\nHeart And Home\nThere is a sign today that is be\nlieved to stimulate clear' thinking.\nPublic opinion as well as home de\ni cisions should be well-founded,\nstable and progressive. This even\nmg is most auspicious for social\naffairs and especially lucky for\nj weddings. The head should rule the\ni heart.\nBusiness Affairs\ni This week should begin with\ngreat promise to those who guide\nthe financial affairs of the nation.\nEconomy now will be the watch\ni word of trade and commerce.\nNational Issues\nAmerican manners will be more\nand more severely criticized. Young\nI folks who ignore formality will be\nj lorced to learn that respect for\ntraditions and established ideals\nof human relations means much in\nthe advancement of careers.\nInternational Affairs\nClose relations between the U.\nS. and Brazil will prove amazingly\nj profitable, it is forecast. Solidarity\nof interests among nations in the\nWestern Hemisphere will prove\nmost fortunate next year.\nPersons whose birthdate it is\ni have the augury of a year of sur\nprising experiences. The aged will\nhave unexpected benefits.\nChildren born on this day prob\nably will be idealistic and talented.\nThey should have extraordinary\ncareeiis.\n(Copyright, 1945'\ni lived until bombing survey officials\nnosed him out.\n\nCAPITOL CHAFF\nThe Army officer, reported in\nthis column to have spent his time\nwith the U. S. Strategic Bombing\nSurvey collecting German por\ntraits, has now been busted.\nOfficials promise that no enlisted\nmen photographers who served\nwith the bombing survey in Europe\nwill have to go to the Pacific.\nA hot row is on between the Navy\nand the Treasury over the Coast\nGuard. Peacetime duty of the Coast\nGuard is to patrol the coasts, keep\ndown rum-running, save shipments\nat sea, etc. Therefore it was under\nthe Treasury. But the Navy took\nit over in wartime and wants to\nkeep it.\n(Copyright, 19IS. hy Bril Syndicate, tuc.)\n20 YEARS AGO {Te empire\nSEPTEMBER 22. 1925\nNew York\u2014Senator Arthur Capper, R of Kansas, and Senator\nThomas J. Walsh, D., of Montana returned from Europe with the opinion\nthat a generous spirit should be exercised in collecting war debts.\nSen. Walsh said \"In a very just sense we added to the debts, citing\nprohibition as one of the ways, as dry laws cut off valuable revenue of\nproducing exports of debtor nations.\nThe fall reunon o\u00a3 the Scottish Rit\u00b0 Bodies of Juneau were to open\nthe following day. with afternoon and evening sessions scheduled foi\nthe next three days, ending with a banquet the final night. A number\nof out-of-town candidates for degrees were to be in attendance.\nThe steamer Jefferson arrived in port this night from Lynn Canal\nports, and sailed south shortly after with 26 passengers for Seattle and\nwayports.\nProf. Takahashi, of San Francisco, was appearing this night in a\nJiu-jitsu match and eatch-as-catch-can wrestling at the Coliseum Theatre,\nagainst three men, all of them sailors from the U. S. S. Unalga.\nTlr> Douglas High School Student Body in a meeting presided over\nby Elizabeth Frazer, President, voted to publish the school papei, Gas\ntineau Breeze, again this year. On the staff were Beth Anderson, Aithui\nNess, Gordon Gray, John Martin and Walter Savikko.\nSam Guyot, J. F. Chamberlain and J. W. Gucker were outgoing\npassengers on the steamer Jefferson.\nWeather: Highest, 58: lowest, 46: cloudy.\nr\u2014\u2014\nDaily Lessons in English w. l. cordon\nWORDS OFTEN MISUSED: Do not write, \"Our's is the best,\u201d or,\n\u201cTheir\u2019s is the best.\" Write OURS, or THEIRS. The apostrophe is not\nrequired.\nOFTEN MISPRONOUNCED: Precise. Pronounce the S as in SO,\n/lot as Z.\nOFTEN MISSPELLED: Serf (slave). Surf (the swell of the sea\nbreaking on the shore\nSYNONYMS: Fickle, inconstant, changeable, capricious, unreliable,\nunstable, variable, vacillating.\nWORD STUDY: \"Use a word three times and it is yours.\u201d Let us\nincrease our vocabulary by mastering one word each day. Today\u2019s word:\nENIGMA: anything inexplicable. \"Who has solved the enigma of life?\"\nETIQUETTE 6 ROBERTA lee\nQ. Should a banana be skinned and eaten with the fingers when\nit is served whole?\nA. No; the banana is not a finger food. Strip off the skin, place\nthe banana on the dessert plate and cut, one bite at a time, with the\nside of the fork.\nQ. Is it necessary for a woman to say \"please\" and \u201cthank you\u201d to\nher servants?\nA. It is not exactly necessary, but this courtesy should not be\nomitted when speaking to persons who are working for her comfort.\nQ. Is it proper to seat a husband and wife side by side at the\ndinner table?\nA. No: it is customary to separate them.\nLOOK and LEARN a* c. gokdon\n1. Are all lakes mediterranean?\n2. Is a boa constrictor poisonous?\n3. Who was America\u2019s first minister to England?\n4. Where is Devil\u2019s Island?\n5. What is meant by Plimsoll's line?\nANSWERS:\n1. Yes; mediterranean means in the middle of land.\n2. No; It crushes its prey.\n3. John Adams.\n4. Off the coast of South Africa.\n5. The water line on ships.\nThere is no substitute for newspaper advertising!\nELLIS AIR LINES\nDAILY TRIPS JUNEAU TO KETCHIKAN\nvia Petersburg and Wrangell\nWith connections to Craig, Klawock, Hydaburg and\nsteamers for Prince Rupert, Vancouver, and Seattle\nFOR RESERVATIONS PHONE 612\nN. GLADYS KNIGHT\nas a pain-up suoscrn.er to THE DAILY ALASKA\nEMPIRE is invited to be our guest